@ifnotinfo
@settitle Function Convert
@top Function Convert
@end ifnotinfo

@deffn Function function_convert (@var{converters}, @var{expr})
Apply one or more function-conversion rules to the expression @var{expr}.
The argument @var{converters} is either a single conversion rule
@code{f => g} or a list of such rules.

A conversion rule has the form @code{f => g}, where @code{f} is the
source function and @code{g} is either a target function name or a
lambda expression. 

The operator @code{=>} indicates a @emph{semantic} conversion, not a
literal renaming. For example, the rule @code{sinc => sin} does not
replace the symbol @code{sinc} by @code{sin}.  Instead, it applies the
 @code{sinc(x) = sin(x)/x}; specifically
@example
(%i1) function_convert('sinc => 'sin, sinc(x) + 1);
                                  sin(x)
(%o1)                             ────── + 1
                                    x
@end example

Users may also supply an explicit conversion by giving a lambda
expression on the right-hand side. For example:

@example
(%i2) function_convert('erfc => lambda([q], 1-erf(q)), erfc(x)^2);
                                             2
(%o2)                            (1 - erf(x))
@end example

Multiple conversions may be given in a Maxima list; they are applied from left to right.

@strong{Example}

@example
(%i3) function_convert(['sinc => 'sin,'sin => 'exp], sinc(x));
                                %i x     - %i x
                             (%e     - %e      ) %i
(%o3)                      - ──────────────────────
                                      2 x
@end example

@end deffn

@deffn Function list_converters [name_1, name_2, ...]

Return a list of all registered function converters known to @code{function_convert}.  In addition to 
returning this list, each converter is printed as a pair @code{FROM => TO} followed by a short description 
taken from the converter's docstring.

When called with no arguments, @code{list_converters} returns the full
set of converters.  When one or more names are supplied, only those
converters whose source function matches one of the given names are
returned.

@example
(%i1) list_converters();
sinc => sin : Convert sinc(x) into sin(x)/x.
csc  => sin : Convert csc(x) into 1/sin(x).
cos  => exp : Convert cos(x) to exponential form.
tan  => sin : Convert tan(x) into sin(x)/cos(x).
sin  => exp : Convert sin(x) to exponential form.
(%o1) [sinc => sin, csc => sin, cos => exp, tan => sin, sin => exp]

(%i2) list_converters(sinc, tan);
sinc => sin : Convert sinc(x) into sin(x)/x.
tan  => sin : Convert tan(x) into sin(x)/cos(x).
(%o2) [sinc => sin, tan => sin]
@end example

The list of converters is maintained internally and entries appear in an unspecified order.  

@code{function_convert}.  


@seealso{function_convert}
@end deffn

@defun describe_converter (eq)
Describe the converter specified by @var{eq}.

@var{eq} must be a single converter equation of the form @code{f => g}.
The operators @code{f} and @code{g} are validated and normalized through
the converter alias system.  If a converter from @code{f} to @code{g}
is defined, information about it is printed: the converter itself,
whether it is built-in or user-defined, and the function's docstring
if one is present.

If no such converter exists, a message stating this is printed.

The function returns the symbol @code{$done}.
@end defun

@defun delete_converter (eqs)
Delete one or more user-defined converters.

The argument @var{eqs} may be either a single converter equation of the
form @code{f = g} or a list of such equations.  Each equation is checked
for proper structure, and for every pair @code{f}, @code{g} the
corresponding user-defined converter is removed.  Converter names are
normalized through @code{$nounify} before deletion.

If a listed converter does not exist as a user-defined converter, no
error is signaled; the converter is simply not present and therefore
nothing is removed.

The function returns the symbol @code{$done}.
@end defun

@defun delete_all_user_converters ()
Delete all user-defined converters.

This function removes every converter that is not marked as built-in.
All entries in the converter hash table are examined, and any converter
whose key does not appear in @code{*built-in-converters*} is deleted.
Built-in converters are preserved.

A message is printed indicating that all user-defined converters have
been removed.  The function does not return a value.
@end defun

@defun register_converter (a b fn &optional doc)
Register a new converter.

The arguments @var{a} and @var{b} must each be converter specifications
of the form @code{f => g}.  The operators are validated, and the
@code{from} operator is normalized through @code{$verbify}.  If a
converter from @code{f} to @code{g} already exists, an error is signaled:
built‑in converters cannot be redefined, and redefining a user‑defined
converter also signals an error.

If @var{b} contains alias operators, they are registered before the
converter itself.  The argument @var{fn} must be a Maxima lambda form;
otherwise an error is signaled.  The converter is then installed in the
converter registry.  If @var{doc} is supplied, it is stored as the
documentation string for this converter.

The function returns the symbol @code{$done}.
@end defun

@defun register_converter (spec fn &optional doc)
Register a new converter.

The argument @var{spec} is either a single converter specification of the
form @code{f = g}, or a two-element Maxima list @code{[f = g, p = q]}.
In the first case, the converter has no alias and the specification
@code{f = g} is used for both registration and lookup.  In the second
case, the first element of the list is the primary converter and the
second element is its alias; the alias is registered before the primary
converter.

Each converter specification is validated, and the @code{from} operator
is normalized through @code{$verbify}.  If a converter from @code{f} to
@code{g} already exists, an error is signaled: built-in converters cannot
be redefined, and redefining a user-defined converter also signals an
error.

The argument @var{fn} must be a Maxima lambda form; otherwise an error is
signaled.  After validation, the converter is installed in the converter
registry.  If @var{doc} is supplied, it is stored as the documentation
string for this converter.

The function returns the symbol @code{$done}.
@end defun




